Aren't we?

246
00:27:20,671 --> 00:27:25,092
Are you saying
that this is all just a dream?

247
00:27:25,342 --> 00:27:28,887
You said it, kid. Not me.

248
00:27:31,348 --> 00:27:32,808
Ah.

249
00:27:33,016 --> 00:27:36,395
So let's go find that girl.

250
00:27:42,692 --> 00:27:44,778
One other thing.

251
00:27:46,029 --> 00:27:48,198
Do you believe in ghosts?

252
00:27:51,952 --> 00:27:53,787
Interesting.

253
00:27:56,456 --> 00:27:57,958
Wait.

254
00:28:00,377 --> 00:28:01,628
Wait!

255
00:28:08,551 --> 00:28:10,136
Wait!

256
00:28:15,141 --> 00:28:16,685
I have to wake up.

257
00:28:16,893 --> 00:28:18,895
Yeah. I have to wake up.

258
00:28:19,229 --> 00:28:22,482
Wake up. Wake up. Wake up.

259
00:28:22,732 --> 00:28:24,901
Wake up!

260
00:28:27,403 --> 00:28:31,658
Wake up, wake up.
Wake up, wake up!

261
00:28:40,500 --> 00:28:43,962
Kid!

262
00:28:44,170 --> 00:28:46,339
Kid, get your head out of the clouds!

263
00:28:46,506 --> 00:28:48,049
Wake up, kid!

264
00:28:48,257 --> 00:28:52,011
There's no sleepwalking
on the Polar Express.

265
00:28:53,012 --> 00:28:54,847
We gotta jump them knuckles.

266
00:28:57,600 --> 00:28:59,519
Come on, kid. Flip my shoulders.

267
00:28:59,685 --> 00:29:01,521
Grab my lily.

268
00:29:04,190 --> 00:29:06,651
That skirt you're chasing
must have moved on ahead.

269
00:29:07,360 --> 00:29:11,239
- We gotta hightail it to the hog, pronto.
- To the hog?

270
00:29:12,114 --> 00:29:15,409
The engine. The engine, you tenderfoot.

271
00:29:15,618 --> 00:29:18,788
We gotta make the engine
before we hit Flat Top Tunnel.

272
00:29:18,955 --> 00:29:20,623
How come?

273
00:29:20,790 --> 00:29:23,417
So many questions.

274
00:29:23,876 --> 00:29:28,172
There is but one inch of clearance
between the roof of this rattler...

275
00:29:28,381 --> 00:29:31,217
...and the roof of Flat Top Tunnel.

276
00:29:31,384 --> 00:29:33,260
Savvy?

277
00:29:36,388 --> 00:29:39,433
It's just the run up to the hump, kid.

278
00:29:40,309 --> 00:29:41,936
This will be interesting.

279
00:30:05,167 --> 00:30:06,835
Get back on, kid. Hurry!

280
00:30:07,002 --> 00:30:09,296
Grab my muck stick.

281
00:30:45,040 --> 00:30:47,501
There's only one trick to this, kid.

282
00:30:48,710 --> 00:30:50,170
When I say "jump"...

283
00:30:52,631 --> 00:30:56,510
...you jump!

284
00:30:56,718 --> 00:30:58,553
Ah!

285
00:31:19,324 --> 00:31:22,494
You. I thought you got thrown off, and...

286
00:31:22,911 --> 00:31:25,705
- You're driving the train?
- They put me in charge.

287
00:31:25,914 --> 00:31:29,292
- The engineer had to check the light.
Here's the light. Careful.

288
00:31:29,501 --> 00:31:31,127
All right, now.

289
00:31:31,419 --> 00:31:34,130
- Oh!
- Oh! I got it.

290
00:31:37,509 --> 00:31:40,970
- How do you know how?
- It's easy. Come here, I'll show you.

291
00:31:41,179 --> 00:31:43,598
This big lever here, that's the throttle.

292
00:31:43,765 --> 00:31:45,892
This little one here, that's the brake.

293
00:31:46,100 --> 00:31:48,937
And those are the pressure gauges.

294
00:31:49,103 --> 00:31:51,689
And that rope is the whistle.

295
00:31:52,357 --> 00:31:54,692
- The whistle.
- Mm-hm.

296
00:31:54,859 --> 00:31:56,778
You wanna try it?

297
00:31:59,614 --> 00:32:01,991
I've wanted to do that my whole life.

298
00:32:06,120 --> 00:32:09,332
Hold still! Hold still! Don't move!

299
00:32:10,541 --> 00:32:11,542
Look!

300
00:32:23,804 --> 00:32:27,224
Stop the train! Stop the train!

301
00:32:28,309 --> 00:32:30,102
Stop the train!

302
00:32:33,064 --> 00:32:34,774
What?

303
00:32:34,982 --> 00:32:36,400
They want us to stop the train.

304
00:32:38,069 --> 00:32:40,237
- Which one is the brake?
- He told me this was.

305
00:32:40,404 --> 00:32:42,114
- Who?
- The engineer.

306
00:32:42,323 --> 00:32:46,911
- The engineer? This one looks like a brake.
- No, he said this was the brake.

307
00:32:47,077 --> 00:32:48,120
Are you sure?

308
00:32:48,496 --> 00:32:50,915
- Uh...
- Are you sure?

309
00:32:58,005 --> 00:33:00,716
Pull the brake!

310
00:33:00,925 --> 00:33:02,801
Stop the train!

311
00:33:20,194 --> 00:33:22,112
Caribou?

312
00:33:24,031 --> 00:33:26,241
- Ugh.
There's no Christmas...

313
00:33:26,450 --> 00:33:28,535
...without the Polar Express
arriving on time.

314
00:33:28,702 --> 00:33:31,997
Am I the only one who understands that?

315
00:33:32,206 --> 00:33:34,958
You. I should have known.

316
00:33:35,125 --> 00:33:39,004
Are you bound and determined that
this train never reaches the North Pole?

317
00:33:39,212 --> 00:33:40,756
But look.

318
00:33:42,049 --> 00:33:43,592
Caribou crossing?!

319
00:33:44,551 --> 00:33:48,263
I make that herd to be at least
100,000, maybe even a million.

320
00:33:48,472 --> 00:33:51,516
It's gonna be hours
before they clear this track.

321
00:33:51,725 --> 00:33:55,729
- A tough nut to crack.
- We are in some serious jelly.

322
00:33:55,896 --> 00:33:58,356
- And a jam.
- Tight spot.

323
00:33:58,565 --> 00:33:59,858
- Up a creek.
- Up a tree.

324
00:34:00,066 --> 00:34:05,030
- Lost in the grass.
- I'll tell you what's grass: Our a... Ow!

325
00:34:45,695 --> 00:34:50,074
Problem solved. All ahead, slow.

326
00:35:35,995 --> 00:35:37,872
We're going pretty fast.

327
00:35:38,080 --> 00:35:40,916
Tell the engineer to slow down.

328
00:35:46,297 --> 00:35:47,882
Slow it down.

329
00:35:49,759 --> 00:35:52,511
Watch the speed!

330
00:35:56,932 --> 00:36:00,603
Ah! Jumping jeepers,
the cotter pin sheared off.

331
00:36:00,769 --> 00:36:02,062
- What?
- The pin.

332
00:36:02,271 --> 00:36:04,398
- Where?
- There.

333
00:36:04,565 --> 00:36:06,108
- Oh, no.
- Oh, no.

334
00:36:07,151 --> 00:36:10,946
- They can't hear me.
- They can't? Oh...

335
00:36:13,407 --> 00:36:15,909
I don't like the look
of this. Quick, under the safety bar.

336
00:36:18,120 --> 00:36:20,372
Is everything all right?
What should we do?

337
00:36:23,208 --> 00:36:24,668
Considering we've
lost communication with the engineer...

338
00:36:24,877 --> 00:36:28,088
...we are standing totally exposed
on the front of the locomotive...

339
00:36:28,255 --> 00:36:31,425
...the train appears to be
accelerating uncontrollably...

340
00:36:31,633 --> 00:36:35,429
...and we are rapidly
approaching Glacier Gulch...

341
00:36:35,637 --> 00:36:39,099
...which just happens to be the steepest
downhill grade in the world...

342
00:36:39,308 --> 00:36:42,561
...I suggest we all hold on...

343
00:36:43,145 --> 00:36:44,605
...tightly!

344
00:37:05,542 --> 00:37:07,377
- The pin.
- The pin.

345
00:37:27,105 --> 00:37:30,775
Jiminy Christmas, the ice has frozen
over the tracks.

346
00:37:53,214 --> 00:37:55,341
Hold on. Hold on. No, no.

347
00:37:56,301 --> 00:37:58,386
Come on. Watch your step.

348
00:37:58,553 --> 00:38:01,764
Come on, sweetie.
Up you go. Up you go.

349
00:38:02,974 --> 00:38:06,686
- Shh.
- Put your feet on here. On here.

350
00:38:09,230 --> 00:38:10,523
Little adventure, huh?

351
00:38:10,732 --> 00:38:13,109
Young man, quick thinking on your part.

352
00:38:34,255 --> 00:38:36,966
Step to your left, please. To your left.

353
00:38:39,343 --> 00:38:40,636
Oh!

354
00:38:40,845 --> 00:38:44,306
Well, that is more like it.

355
00:38:46,684 --> 00:38:48,728
What in the name of Mike?

356
00:38:52,523 --> 00:38:53,983
Look.

357
00:38:56,610 --> 00:38:59,363
Get us the blazes out of here!

358
00:39:07,621 --> 00:39:09,206
Turn this sled around.

359
00:39:27,725 --> 00:39:29,101
Look there.

360
00:39:31,812 --> 00:39:33,147
Tracks.

361
00:39:33,355 --> 00:39:34,731
Dead ahead.

362
00:39:40,571 --> 00:39:41,697
Right.

363
00:39:47,494 --> 00:39:48,537
Left.

364
00:39:54,001 --> 00:39:55,043
Right.

365
00:39:58,922 --> 00:40:00,173
Hang a Louie.

366
00:40:03,343 --> 00:40:04,678
Toss a Ritchie.

367
00:40:08,098 --> 00:40:09,724
Port astern.

368
00:40:11,935 --> 00:40:13,728
To the starboard.

369
00:40:15,063 --> 00:40:17,607
My slipper.
- You're gonna lose your ticket.

370
00:40:17,774 --> 00:40:19,651
It's not my ticket, it's yours.

371
00:40:19,860 --> 00:40:21,653
- It's my ticket?
- Yes.

372
00:40:21,820 --> 00:40:23,947
Right. Keep up with me. Left.

373
00:40:24,281 --> 00:40:26,700
Right. Left.

374
00:40:30,787 --> 00:40:32,080
Right.

375
00:40:32,455 --> 00:40:33,707
Left.

376
00:40:33,873 --> 00:40:35,250
Right.

377
00:40:35,458 --> 00:40:37,377
Left. Right.

378
00:40:41,131 --> 00:40:42,382
- Oh, no!
- Oh, no!

379
00:40:44,634 --> 00:40:46,428
Brace yourselves!

380
00:40:57,397 --> 00:40:59,315
Well, that's more like it.

381
00:41:01,734 --> 00:41:03,236
Thank you.

382
00:41:03,403 --> 00:41:06,698
Thank you. I can't believe
you found my ticket.

383
00:41:07,240 --> 00:41:09,867
Did someone say they found a ticket?

384
00:41:11,869 --> 00:41:15,289
Well, in that case... Tickets, please.

385
00:41:24,173 --> 00:41:25,716
Thank you.

386
00:41:27,426 --> 00:41:31,347
"L-E"?
- Hey, just like that know-it-all kid.

387
00:41:46,362 --> 00:41:47,697
Watch your step.

388
00:41:47,863 --> 00:41:51,158
Tricky walking up here. It's mighty slick.
Mighty slick, I tell you.

389
00:41:51,367 --> 00:41:55,204
Oh, whoop... There you go.
What did I tell you?

390
00:41:55,413 --> 00:42:00,501
Years ago, on my first Christmas Eve run,
I was up on the roof making my rounds...

391
00:42:00,709 --> 00:42:02,586
...when I slipped on the ice myself.

392
00:42:02,795 --> 00:42:06,173
I reached out for a hand iron,
but it broke off. I slid and fell.

393
00:42:06,382 --> 00:42:10,344
And yet, I did not fall off this train.

394
00:42:10,970 --> 00:42:13,180
Someone saved you?

395
00:42:13,389 --> 00:42:15,349
Or something.

396
00:42:18,227 --> 00:42:19,520
An angel.

397
00:42:20,437 --> 00:42:22,106
Maybe.

398
00:42:22,273 --> 00:42:24,358
Wait. Wait.

399
00:42:25,234 --> 00:42:28,362
What did he look like? Did you see him?

400
00:42:29,488 --> 00:42:33,367
No, sir. But sometimes
seeing is believing.

401
00:42:33,742 --> 00:42:38,872
And sometimes the most real things
in the world are the things we can't see.

402
00:42:44,169 --> 00:42:47,047
Ah, the forsaken and the abandoned.

403
00:42:48,257 --> 00:42:52,219
Mind your step, now.
These poor toys have suffered enough...

404
00:42:52,427 --> 00:42:56,723
...being left to rust and decay in the
back alleys and vacant lots of the world.

405
00:42:57,266 --> 00:42:59,017
What are they doing here?

406
00:42:59,184 --> 00:43:01,395
It's a new concept
the boss came up with.

407
00:43:01,603 --> 00:43:04,940
Instead of being thrown away,
they're collected. Refurbished.

408
00:43:05,691 --> 00:43:10,737
He calls it "rebicycling. "
Something like that.

409
00:43:13,031 --> 00:43:15,408
Makes me wanna cry...

410
00:43:15,617 --> 00:43:18,745
...seeing toys that were
treated this way.

411
00:43:19,538 --> 00:43:21,623
These hopelessly entangled...

412
00:43:21,790 --> 00:43:23,750
...string puppets and marionettes...

413
00:43:23,959 --> 00:43:28,213
...pose a particular problem. We found
the nimble fingers of our work force...

414
00:43:28,380 --> 00:43:32,717
...here at the North Pole are best
for working out those knots and tangles.

415
00:43:32,926 --> 00:43:35,428
Thank you. Uh-oh.
Double-locked here.

416
00:43:46,815 --> 00:43:50,276
You are just like me, my friend.

417
00:43:50,485 --> 00:43:52,821
- A scrooge!
- Ah!

418
00:43:52,987 --> 00:43:55,156
Ebenezer Scrooge.

419
00:43:55,323 --> 00:43:58,660
North Pole, Santa Claus, this train...

420
00:43:58,827 --> 00:44:02,747
...it's all a bunch of humbug.
A bout of indigestion.

421
00:44:02,914 --> 00:44:05,500
Oh, yeah. I know what you are.

422
00:44:05,667 --> 00:44:08,294
You're a doubter.

423
00:44:08,503 --> 00:44:11,005
A doubter. You don't believe!

424
00:44:11,214 --> 00:44:14,342
You're a doubter! You don't believe!

425
00:44:31,442 --> 00:44:34,362
Hey, you missed it.
We rode down some really sharp hills.

426
00:44:34,529 --> 00:44:36,197
We were on what looked like
a frozen lake.

427
00:44:36,364 --> 00:44:38,908
But I know it was just an optical illusion
caused by moonlight.

428
00:44:39,116 --> 00:44:41,994
He said the train was on ice.
But I said that's impossible...

429
00:44:42,203 --> 00:44:44,872
You can't put a train track...
Hey, where you going now?

430
00:44:57,885 --> 00:44:59,220
Shh.

431
00:44:59,387 --> 00:45:02,348
<i>I'm wishing on a star</i>

432
00:45:02,556 --> 00:45:05,684
<i>And trying to believe</i>

433
00:45:05,893 --> 00:45:09,021
<i>That even though it's far</i>

434
00:45:09,480 --> 00:45:12,024
<i>He'll find me Christmas Eve</i>

435
00:45:12,650 --> 00:45:15,778
<i>I guess that Santa's busy</i>

436
00:45:15,986 --> 00:45:18,948
<i>'Cause he's never come around</i>

437
00:45:19,490 --> 00:45:25,204
<i>I think of him
When Christmas comes to town</i>

438
00:45:26,038 --> 00:45:29,166
<i>The best time of the year</i>

439
00:45:29,333 --> 00:45:32,544
<i>When everyone comes home</i>

440
00:45:32,753 --> 00:45:35,881
<i>With all this Christmas cheer</i>

441
00:45:36,090 --> 00:45:39,593
<i>It's hard to be alone</i>

442
00:45:39,760 --> 00:45:45,808
<i>Putting up the Christmas tree
With friends who come around</i>

443
00:45:46,016 --> 00:45:52,356
<i>It's so much fun
When Christmas comes to town</i>

444
00:45:53,190 --> 00:45:59,238
<i>Presents for the children
Wrapped in red and green</i>

445
00:45:59,780 --> 00:46:05,577
<i>All the things I've heard about
But never really seen</i>

446
00:46:06,453 --> 00:46:08,914
<i>No one will be sleeping</i>

447
00:46:09,122 --> 00:46:12,167
<i>On the night of Christmas Eve</i>

448
00:46:12,376 --> 00:46:19,424
<i>Hoping Santa's on his way</i>

449
00:46:19,633 --> 00:46:22,677
<i>When Santa's sleighbells ring</i>

450
00:46:22,886 --> 00:46:25,722
<i>I listen all around</i>

451
00:46:25,889 --> 00:46:29,100
<i>The herald angels sing</i>

452
00:46:29,309 --> 00:46:32,270
<i>I never hear a sound</i>

453
00:46:32,812 --> 00:46:36,274
<i>And all the dreams of children</i>

454
00:46:36,483 --> 00:46:39,235
<i>Once lost will all be found</i>

455
00:46:39,402 --> 00:46:45,325
<i>That's all I want
When Christmas comes to town</i>

456
00:46:47,744 --> 00:46:56,377
<i>That's all I want
When Christmas comes to town</i>

457
00:47:07,931 --> 00:47:09,349
Look.

458
00:47:12,018 --> 00:47:14,020
The northern lights.

459
00:47:16,856 --> 00:47:18,900
Hey. You three.

460
00:47:20,109 --> 00:47:21,903
We just crossed it.

461
00:47:22,111 --> 00:47:27,492
Latitude 66°33'.
The Arctic Circle.

462
00:47:27,700 --> 00:47:30,995
And do you see?
Those lights in the distance.

463
00:47:31,954 --> 00:47:36,375
They look like the lights of a strange
ocean liner sailing on a frozen sea.

464
00:47:37,710 --> 00:47:39,670
There...

465
00:47:40,379 --> 00:47:42,381
...is the North Pole.

466
00:47:47,386 --> 00:47:50,223
<i>It's a magic carpet on a rail
It never takes a rest</i>

467
00:47:50,389 --> 00:47:53,559
<i>Flying through
The mountains and the snow</i>

468
00:47:53,726 --> 00:47:56,687
<i>You can ride for free and join the fun
If you just say yes</i>

469
00:47:56,896 --> 00:48:00,191
<i>'Cause that's the way things happen
On the Polar Express</i>

470
00:48:00,399 --> 00:48:03,486
<i>Whoo, whoo, the whistle blows
That's the sound of her singing</i>

471
00:48:03,652 --> 00:48:06,864
<i>Ding, ding, the bell will ring
Golly, look at her go</i>

472
00:48:07,073 --> 00:48:10,034
<i>You wonder if you'll get there soon
Anybody's guess</i>

473
00:48:10,242 --> 00:48:13,412
<i>'Cause that's the way things happen
On the Polar Express</i>

474
00:48:13,579 --> 00:48:16,707
<i>When we get there
We'll scream, "Yay!"</i>

475
00:48:16,916 --> 00:48:19,210
<i>We'll arrive with
A bang, bang, bang</i>

476
00:48:19,418 --> 00:48:22,379
<i>Boom, boom, boom
Laughing all the way</i>

477
00:48:27,426 --> 00:48:30,304
We made it. With five minutes to spare.

478
00:48:30,512 --> 00:48:31,847
We made it.

479
00:48:57,789 --> 00:49:00,083
There should be elves.
Where are the elves?

480
00:49:00,292 --> 00:49:01,919
Yeah, where are the elves?

481
00:49:02,127 --> 00:49:04,421
They are gathering
in the center of the city.

482
00:49:04,630 --> 00:49:08,383
That is where Santa will give
the first gift of Christmas.

483
00:49:09,301 --> 00:49:11,720
Who gets the first gift of Christmas?

484
00:49:11,887 --> 00:49:15,766
He will choose one of you.

485
00:49:18,810 --> 00:49:21,772
- Look.
- Elves!

486
00:49:52,677 --> 00:49:54,971
All right. All right,
ladies and gentlemen.

487
00:49:55,180 --> 00:49:57,849
Two columns, if you please.

488
00:49:58,016 --> 00:50:00,810
Shorter in the front, taller in the rear.

489
00:50:01,352 --> 00:50:04,939
Even-numbered birthdays on the right,
odd-numbered on the left.

490
00:50:05,106 --> 00:50:08,026
No pushing. No pushing.
But let's not dilly-dally.

491
00:50:08,193 --> 00:50:10,111
It's five minutes to midnight.

492
00:50:10,278 --> 00:50:13,865
Hey, what gives? It was five minutes
till midnight four minutes ago.

493
00:50:14,365 --> 00:50:16,826
Exactly. Columns of two.

494
00:50:17,035 --> 00:50:19,120
- One, two.
Excuse me.

495
00:50:19,287 --> 00:50:21,748
- Question.
